<Layout title="Respiratory & Airway Assessment Tools" description="Respiratory and airway assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Respiratory &amp; Airway</div>
  <h1>Respiratory &amp; Airway Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Tools for early deterioration warning, airway management, respiratory severity, and ventilator weaning readiness.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>NEWS2 (National Early Warning Score 2)</strong> — Six physiological parameters (SpO₂, supplemental O₂, temperature, systolic BP, pulse, AVPU/consciousness) plus respiratory rate. Score ≥5 triggers urgent clinical review.</li>
      <li><strong>MEWS (Modified Early Warning Score)</strong> — Precursor to NEWS; monitors respiratory rate, SpO₂, heart rate, systolic BP, temperature, and AVPU score to detect clinical deterioration.</li>
      <li><strong>CURB-65</strong> — Pneumonia severity score: Confusion, Urea &gt;7 mmol/L, Respiratory rate ≥30, Blood pressure &lt;90/60, age ≥65. Score 0–1 = low risk (outpatient); ≥3 = high risk (ICU consideration).</li>
      <li><strong>Borg Scale</strong> — Perceived exertion/dyspnea rated 0–10 by patient during exercise or respiratory assessment. Widely used in pulmonary rehabilitation.</li>
      <li><strong>MRC Dyspnea Scale</strong> — Five-grade scale rating breathlessness impact on activity. Grade 1 = breathless only with strenuous exercise; Grade 5 = too breathless to leave the house.</li>
      <li><strong>STOP-BANG Questionnaire</strong> — Obstructive sleep apnea risk screening: Snoring, Tiredness, Observed apnea, Pressure (hypertension), BMI &gt;35, Age &gt;50, Neck &gt;40 cm, Gender male. Score ≥3 = high risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Berlin Questionnaire</strong> — Three-category sleep apnea risk assessment including snoring severity, daytime sleepiness, and presence of hypertension/obesity.</li>
      <li><strong>CAT (COPD Assessment Test)</strong> — Eight-item COPD symptom impact questionnaire. Scores 0–40; guides COPD management intensity.</li>
      <li><strong>LEMON Assessment</strong> — Difficult airway prediction mnemonic: Look, Evaluate (3-3-2 rule), Mallampati, Obstruction, Neck mobility.</li>
      <li><strong>Mallampati Score</strong> — Mouth opening and pharyngeal visualization graded I–IV. Higher scores predict difficult intubation; Class III–IV warrant airway preparation.</li>
      <li><strong>ROTH Score</strong> — Patient counts 1–30 as quickly as possible; time to 30 and highest number reached serve as a bedside respiratory screening proxy.</li>
      <li><strong>Silverman-Anderson Score</strong> — Neonatal respiratory distress scale; assesses upper chest retraction, lower chest retraction, xiphoid retraction, nares dilation, and expiratory grunt (0–2 each; 0–10 total).</li>
      <li><strong>Downes Score</strong> — Infant respiratory distress assessment using cyanosis, air entry, retractions, grunting, and respiratory rate. Score &gt;6 indicates severe distress.</li>
      <li><strong>Tobin Index (f/VT)</strong> — Ratio of respiratory frequency to tidal volume. Values &lt;100 predict successful weaning from mechanical ventilation.</li>
      <li><strong>RSB Index (Rapid Shallow Breathing Index)</strong> — Same as Tobin index (f/VT); &lt;80 breaths/min/L predicts successful spontaneous breathing trial.</li>
      <li><strong>SBT Readiness Criteria</strong> — Pre-assessment for spontaneous breathing trial: adequate oxygenation (PaO₂/FiO₂ &gt;150), PEEP ≤5–8 cmH₂O, FiO₂ ≤40–50%, hemodynamic stability, ability to initiate breathing effort.</li>
      <li><strong>P/F Ratio (PaO₂/FiO₂)</strong> — Oxygenation index for ARDS classification: &gt;300 normal; 200–300 mild ARDS; 100–200 moderate ARDS; &lt;100 severe ARDS.</li>
      <li><strong>Murray Lung Injury Score</strong> — Quantifies lung injury severity using PaO₂/FiO₂, PEEP, respiratory compliance, and chest X-ray consolidation. Score &gt;2.5 indicates severe lung injury.</li>
      <li><strong>Berlin Definition Criteria for ARDS</strong> — Classification of ARDS by timing (&lt;1 week), imaging (bilateral infiltrates), origin (not explained by fluid overload/cardiac), and oxygenation (P/F ratio with PEEP ≥5).</li>
      <li><strong>CPIS (Clinical Pulmonary Infection Score)</strong> — VAP diagnosis tool using temperature, WBC, tracheal secretions, oxygenation, chest X-ray, and microbiology. Score &gt;6 suggests VAP.</li>
      <li><strong>Pulmonary Score</strong> — Pediatric asthma severity scale evaluating respiratory rate, wheezing, inspiratory-to-expiratory ratio, accessory muscle use, and oxygen saturation.</li>
      <li><strong>PRAM (Pediatric Respiratory Assessment Measure)</strong> — Asthma severity assessment for children based on suprasternal retractions, scalene muscle use, wheezing, and air entry.</li>
      <li><strong>Westley Croup Score</strong> — Five-parameter score for croup severity: level of consciousness, cyanosis, stridor, air entry, retractions. Score &gt;6 indicates severe croup.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
